snippet.textDisplay: The first painting was EXACTLY like the outcome of a failed art project I made in freshman year of high school. We were given cups and DC motors and battery packs and markers and told to make robots that painted. Well, everyone else made the markers into legs on the cup, uncapped pointing down onto the paper they were stood on. Then the motor spun a weight on top, which shook the cup and caused it to walk across the paper, drawing as it went. I had the genius idea of suspending the cup and having it draw a perfect circle from spinning. The force must've caused the ink to gather in their tips, because as soon as they touched the paper, a fraction of a second, ink was everywhere. Across my paper, the person in front of my, my jacket, my shirt. You'd peel up the paper and there would be a clean rectangle on the desk surface, and that ink all over the perimeter.
snippet.textOriginal: The first painting was EXACTLY like the outcome of a failed art project I made in freshman year of high school. We were given cups and DC motors and battery packs and markers and told to make robots that painted. Then the motor spun a weight on top, which shook the cup and caused it to walk across the paper, drawing as it went.
